And some people will really sit here and say, Israel just stumbled into the right choice.

00:36:16.834 --> 00:36:18.456
Dear friend, that's not at all what happens in the story.

00:36:18.516 --> 00:36:20.860
God does it.

00:36:20.880 --> 00:36:21.821
Why is Israel faithful?

00:36:21.942 --> 00:36:22.823
Because God does it.

00:36:24.205 --> 00:36:25.887
Why does Israel make...

00:36:26.028 --> 00:36:26.969
The text is clear.

00:36:27.950 --> 00:36:29.272
It seems that all of them obey.

00:36:29.333 --> 00:36:33.559
There's no indication here that any Israelis die.

00:36:33.619 --> 00:36:35.401
No Jews die here.

00:36:35.862 --> 00:36:36.143
Why?

00:36:36.383 --> 00:36:37.184
Because God does it.

00:36:38.045 --> 00:36:39.508
Because God redeems his people.

00:36:41.430 --> 00:36:44.595
It seems that all of them obey, or at least practically all of them do.

00:36:44.956 --> 00:36:46.578
That's a miracle in and of itself.

00:36:46.882 --> 00:36:53.969
Keep in mind, this is the same people that in just a few chapters are going to be complaining and wanting to go back into slavery.

00:36:54.890 --> 00:36:58.333
How is it that God could bring this people to do that just by chance?

00:36:58.353 --> 00:36:59.154
It doesn't happen.

00:36:59.634 --> 00:37:00.995
God had to do it.

00:37:01.516 --> 00:37:05.820
God brings about their obedience so that he and he alone can deliver them.

00:37:07.601 --> 00:37:16.690
He also provides for their upcoming journey through providentially causing the Egyptians to fear what might happen if the Israelites stay.

00:37:18.306 --> 00:37:24.197
He had turned the greatest nation on earth at the time into a nation cowering like an unarmed homeowner against an armed robber.

00:37:24.617 --> 00:37:25.679
Take whatever you want.

00:37:25.719 --> 00:37:28.825
Just get out of here and don't kill anyone.

00:37:28.845 --> 00:37:29.406
Think of that.

00:37:29.446 --> 00:37:34.515
Think of the greatest nation on earth at the time cowering to its slaves.

00:37:36.339 --> 00:37:37.180
How does that happen?

00:37:38.302 --> 00:37:40.466
God, it's the only answer we have.

00:37:41.154 --> 00:37:43.136
It's the only way we could possibly explain it.

00:37:43.457 --> 00:37:44.378
God did it.

00:37:44.558 --> 00:37:48.562
Yahweh, the faithful, sovereign, covenant making God of Israel did it.

00:37:48.802 --> 00:37:50.064
And he did it for his people.

00:37:51.265 --> 00:37:52.546
The payoff here is very clear.

00:37:52.566 --> 00:37:54.849
It wasn't just that Egypt was overthrown.

00:37:55.309 --> 00:37:58.393
God had been systematically doing that throughout the other parables.

00:37:58.813 --> 00:38:03.879
And while that is certainly an element, it is not the ultimate reason why God achieves the Passover.

00:38:04.399 --> 00:38:05.741
Look it back at the end of verse 11.

00:38:06.882 --> 00:38:10.546
He says, it is the Lord's Passover.

00:38:12.418 --> 00:38:18.829
For I will pass through the land of Egypt that night, and I will strike the firstborn of the land of Egypt, both man and beast.

00:38:18.849 --> 00:38:21.514
And on the gods of Egypt, I will execute judgments for I am Lord.

00:38:21.914 --> 00:38:23.076
He's telling them what he's going to do.

00:38:23.517 --> 00:38:26.302
The blood will be a sign for you on the houses where you are.

00:38:26.342 --> 00:38:35.558
And when I see the blood, I will pass over you and no plague will befall you to destroy you when I strike the land of Egypt.

00:38:35.758 --> 00:38:38.162
Why is God doing all of this?

00:38:38.402 --> 00:38:42.688
to execute judgments on Egypt and it's God's yes, but keep reading.

00:38:43.489 --> 00:38:47.755
God is doing this so that he can do it for his people.

00:38:47.815 --> 00:38:51.920
The blood is not for Egypt to see their good works.

00:38:51.980 --> 00:38:56.006
It's not for Egypt to see who is God's people and who is not.

00:38:56.366 --> 00:38:59.070
It's not even for God to see their good works.

00:38:59.130 --> 00:39:01.453
It's not even so that God can know that they're righteous.

00:39:01.533 --> 00:39:03.756
God does not need blood on a door to know that.

00:39:04.978 --> 00:39:08.242
God does not need blood on a door to know that the people are his people.

00:39:09.794 --> 00:39:10.735
God is all-knowing.

00:39:11.076 --> 00:39:12.257
God does not need the sign.

00:39:12.337 --> 00:39:12.878
What does he say?

00:39:13.138 --> 00:39:15.081
The sign is for you.

00:39:15.181 --> 00:39:20.928
The blood is for you to see the blood, experience the cost of this redemption I'm about to provide.

00:39:21.288 --> 00:39:22.570
The meal was for them.

00:39:23.011 --> 00:39:30.260
They had to eat the whole lamb to taste the costly sacrifice God had ordained on their behalf.

00:39:30.600 --> 00:39:38.610
They had to eat it to exercise the faith that God had given them and more fully experienced the grace that he was offering them in the Passover.

00:39:38.690 --> 00:39:40.092
The memorial was for them.

00:39:40.132 --> 00:39:42.714
The continuing celebration of this was for them.

00:39:43.055 --> 00:39:44.496
God didn't need a reminder.

00:39:45.177 --> 00:39:49.222
God didn't need a calendar reminder to recount his own faithfulness.

00:39:49.562 --> 00:39:52.145
But he knew a people prone to wander wood.

00:39:52.265 --> 00:39:55.288
He knew that his ultimate plans were to come to fruition.

00:39:55.629 --> 00:40:04.338
He would need to give Israel every opportunity to strengthen their faith through the various signs and feasts that he would give to them on top of this one.

00:40:06.466 --> 00:40:08.568
So God gives them the Passover for them.

00:40:08.608 --> 00:40:16.556
God ultimately goes in, God and God alone goes in, slays the firstborn just as he told Egypt would happen in chapter 11.

00:40:16.616 --> 00:40:17.537
He tells him it's going to happen.

00:40:17.597 --> 00:40:18.778
It happens in chapter 12.

00:40:19.299 --> 00:40:20.019
God does it.

00:40:20.059 --> 00:40:21.921
God's very clear that he alone does it.

00:40:24.203 --> 00:40:30.389
And before we get to the point of Passover, there's a potential problem that I think we need to discuss.

00:40:31.450 --> 00:40:33.893
And I want to caveat it by saying it's not a real problem.

00:40:34.093 --> 00:40:35.154
It's just a potential one.

00:40:36.386 --> 00:40:50.087
Atheists and liberal theologians alike, though sadly I repeat myself, often look to the events that are about to come to pass in the promised land with the conquest of the various peoples and bring up the classic problem of evil.

00:40:50.407 --> 00:40:53.973
How could a good God allow bad things to happen to good people?

00:40:54.794 --> 00:40:57.458
They go to what happens in Canaan, right?

00:40:57.986 --> 00:41:03.974
If you have conversations with people about this problem of evil, that's where they go.

00:41:04.235 --> 00:41:07.960
Well, how could God tell His people to go and commit all these atrocities?

00:41:08.661 --> 00:41:09.402
That's where they go.

00:41:12.386 --> 00:41:15.610
Or maybe you've heard it put this way, as I have in conversations with unbelievers.

00:41:17.173 --> 00:41:22.680
I could never follow a God that commands His people to kill or wipe out entire civilizations.

00:41:24.282 --> 00:41:26.866
As I was studying, I couldn't help but wonder

00:41:26.946 --> 00:41:33.634
why I've never seen or heard anybody come to this text with that question.

00:41:33.975 --> 00:41:36.317
Because again, who's the one that does the killing here?

00:41:37.939 --> 00:41:39.902
God doesn't command Israel to kill the Egyptians.

00:41:40.723 --> 00:41:44.327
God himself doesn't.

00:41:44.347 --> 00:41:47.351
If you're going to put God on a hook, here it is, if you're going to.

00:41:47.631 --> 00:41:48.652
You're not going to, by the way.

00:41:48.853 --> 00:41:51.736
But if you were going to try, here would be where you might look.

00:41:52.717 --> 00:41:55.521
But even here, you would be wrong in doing so.

00:41:55.541 --> 00:41:56.562
You would fail.

00:41:56.674 --> 00:41:57.495
in doing so.

00:42:05.627 --> 00:42:11.856
And before we jump to our well rehearsed and true responses of well, there are not really any good people.

00:42:12.877 --> 00:42:14.480
Those are good responses.

00:42:14.500 --> 00:42:16.663
That is the right response that there is no one good.

00:42:19.587 --> 00:42:20.689
That is a true response.

00:42:20.969 --> 00:42:24.434
But before we get there, this morning, I just want us all to stop and feel that tension.

00:42:25.218 --> 00:42:29.704
Would you stop and consider what happened on the night of Passover?

00:42:29.724 --> 00:42:34.249
Would you stop and feel the tension of your lost friends and family members who might ask this question?

00:42:37.433 --> 00:42:38.374
The text is clear.

00:42:39.536 --> 00:42:41.618
God doesn't send Satan to kill the sons.

00:42:42.479 --> 00:42:44.402
God doesn't send a disease to kill them.

00:42:46.965 --> 00:42:54.194
God passes from house to house an exact divine vengeance on Egypt for his people himself.

00:42:56.674 --> 00:43:01.340
And so the question could be asked, how could God do that?

00:43:02.782 --> 00:43:05.986
How could God go and kill those innocent sons?

00:43:06.186 --> 00:43:07.628
How could a holy God do that?

00:43:08.009 --> 00:43:10.111
Why would a holy God do that?

00:43:13.255 --> 00:43:21.426
Might I suggest a better question for us to ponder this morning in response, one that is worth the voting our lives' attention to?

00:43:23.234 --> 00:43:27.461
After all, the answer to the previous question, though hard to grapple with, is simple.

00:43:28.082 --> 00:43:29.103
There is no one good.

00:43:30.385 --> 00:43:42.444
God's justice truly was delivered that night, but true justice would have been not just the total annihilation of Egypt, but the total annihilation of all mankind that night.

00:43:43.606 --> 00:43:46.831
That's what would have been fair that night.

00:43:46.851 --> 00:43:51.378
What would have been fair that night is if God took out Egypt, Israel, and everyone else with them.

00:43:52.258 --> 00:43:53.480
That's what we deserve.

00:43:54.221 --> 00:43:55.282
That's what I deserve.

00:43:59.428 --> 00:44:03.693
But the question that needs posing brings us to the heart of the point of the Passover.

00:44:03.713 --> 00:44:10.723
The question is not how God could kill the firstborn males from a nation that opposed them at every turn to this point in the story.

00:44:11.063 --> 00:44:13.707
And by the way, those children were not innocent, they were sinners.

00:44:13.907 --> 00:44:16.210
Their family, sinners, Pharaoh, a sinner.

00:44:17.826 --> 00:44:29.143
The question comes some 1500 years later, and that is, how could God send His perfect spotless Son, the Lamb of God, to die on a Roman cross at the hands of the nation He delivered from Egypt?

00:44:29.364 --> 00:44:30.505
How could God do that?

00:44:32.248 --> 00:44:36.154
That's the question that deserves our lives' attention this morning.

00:44:36.174 --> 00:44:46.610
That's the question that this text begs of our minds and our attentions this morning is, how could God send His Son, the Lamb of God, to the cross for us?

00:44:47.266 --> 00:44:48.307
How is that fair?

00:44:50.650 --> 00:44:51.291
I know me.

00:44:52.832 --> 00:44:53.834
I'm not worthy of that.

00:44:58.459 --> 00:45:01.022
That's the question that doesn't make any human sense.

00:45:02.504 --> 00:45:11.314
You see, the lambs that were killed on the first Passover and every Passover thereafter for 1500 years were just the shadow of the better lamb that was to come.

00:45:11.778 --> 00:45:14.621
A lamb whose blood could actually redeem a people.

00:45:15.021 --> 00:45:19.406
A lamb whose blood would actually satisfy the wrath of God on account of sins.

00:45:20.387 --> 00:45:29.275
Romans chapter one, verse 16, tells us of the gospel of Jesus and that this gospel is the power of God unto salvation.

00:45:29.296 --> 00:45:30.417
But what is that gospel?

00:45:31.077 --> 00:45:36.603
The gospel is simply this, that God sent his son Jesus to be the lamb of God for us on the cross.

00:45:37.884 --> 00:45:39.826
It is the power of God unto salvation.

00:45:42.498 --> 00:45:44.942
We read later in Romans 3 that none of us is good.

00:45:45.342 --> 00:45:46.103
No, not one.

00:45:46.324 --> 00:45:47.285
None of us seek him.

00:45:48.908 --> 00:45:53.895
We read later in Romans 3 that we all sin and fall short of the mark of his perfection.

00:45:56.760 --> 00:46:06.194
And in light of all of this, we get to Romans 5 and Paul writes this, God shows his love for us and that while we were still sinners, Christ died for us.

00:46:07.170 --> 00:46:19.923
You see, 1500 years later, God sent a Passover lamb on our behalf, who, by the way, would take a Passover meal with his people, his disciples, and instruct them to do so in remembrance of him, which we still observe today as communion.

00:46:20.003 --> 00:46:30.815
He then would go to a cross, die for the sins of his people to redeem a people back to God for his glory, for his honor, and for his praise.

00:46:32.616 --> 00:46:34.098
Why does God do that?

00:46:35.010 --> 00:46:38.278
Because Romans 6-23, the wages of sin is death.

00:46:39.180 --> 00:46:40.924
Our sin has a consequence.

00:46:42.207 --> 00:46:44.833
There is no forgiveness of sins without the shedding of blood.

00:46:45.294 --> 00:46:46.176
It cannot happen.

00:46:46.797 --> 00:46:49.804
Our sin has a price that has to be paid.

00:46:51.588 --> 00:46:52.370
And then we get to

00:46:52.450 --> 00:47:00.961
Romans chapter eight verses one through four, and we get this as his paraphrase, God and Jesus fulfilled the law, which condemns us and our slavery to sin.

00:47:01.342 --> 00:47:04.346
And through the work of his son, we are no longer condemned.

00:47:04.506 --> 00:47:05.787
We are no longer slaves.

00:47:06.148 --> 00:47:07.690
We have been redeemed.

00:47:08.591 --> 00:47:09.953
That is the message of the gospel.

00:47:11.195 --> 00:47:19.986
And then all of that is summarized and summed up in one of the climatic moments of the book of Romans in chapter eight, starting in verse 31, what then shall we say to these things?

00:47:20.098 --> 00:47:22.761
If God is for us, who can be against us?

00:47:23.402 --> 00:47:24.163
Think about Israel.

00:47:24.724 --> 00:47:25.765
Think about the Passover.

00:47:26.246 --> 00:47:33.795
Here they have God's promise deliverance, and they respond when Moses in the text comes to them and says, hey, here's what you're going to do, and here's what God's going to do.

00:47:34.076 --> 00:47:34.596
What do they do?

00:47:34.796 --> 00:47:35.958
They bow down in worship.

00:47:36.679 --> 00:47:36.939
Why?

00:47:37.380 --> 00:47:39.222
Because if God's for them, who can be against them?

00:47:40.283 --> 00:47:41.245
We should say the same thing.

00:47:41.285 --> 00:47:43.387
If God is for us, who can be against us?

00:47:43.467 --> 00:47:45.650
He who did not spare his own son.

00:47:45.762 --> 00:47:51.369
but gave him up for us all, how will he not also with him graciously give us all things?

00:47:52.010 --> 00:47:54.713
Who shall bring any charge against God's elect?

00:47:55.053 --> 00:47:56.635
It is God's who justifies.

00:47:57.056 --> 00:47:58.718
Who is to condemn?

00:47:59.038 --> 00:48:00.860
Christ Jesus is the one who died.

00:48:00.880 --> 00:48:03.223
In other words, who's to condemn us to death?

00:48:03.403 --> 00:48:10.712
Because Jesus died for our behalf and he continues, Christ Jesus who died, more than that, who is raised, who is at the right hand of God.

00:48:11.032 --> 00:48:13.676
Jesus didn't just die on a cross, he's now the judge.

00:48:14.477 --> 00:48:15.698
Who can condemn us then?

00:48:16.034 --> 00:48:18.637
Who can continue to put us under the punishment of sin?

00:48:18.657 --> 00:48:19.317
No one.

00:48:22.281 --> 00:48:23.922
Who shall separate us from the love of Christ?

00:48:23.942 --> 00:48:29.888
Verse 34, 35, shall tribulation or distress or persecution or famine or nakedness or danger or sword.

00:48:30.309 --> 00:48:33.392
As it is written, for your sake, we are being killed all the day long.

00:48:33.933 --> 00:48:36.155
We are regarded as sheep to be slaughtered.

00:48:36.255 --> 00:48:36.455
No.

00:48:37.396 --> 00:48:40.159
And all these things we are more than conquerors through him who loved us.

00:48:40.860 --> 00:48:42.962
For I am sure that neither death nor life

00:48:43.266 --> 00:48:56.238
nor angels, nor rulers, nor things present, nor things to come, nor powers, nor height, nor depth, nor anything else in all creation will be able to separate us from the love of God and Christ Jesus, our Lord.

00:48:57.159 --> 00:48:58.581
So what is the point of Passover?

00:48:59.261 --> 00:49:05.667
The point of Passover is simply this, that our God is a redeeming God and that he alone redeems.

00:49:06.588 --> 00:49:09.211
It is not based on any of our own actions.

00:49:09.731 --> 00:49:10.472
We are sinners.

00:49:10.592 --> 00:49:11.473
We are unworthy.

00:49:11.873 --> 00:49:12.594
God does it.

00:49:12.930 --> 00:49:16.795
and He does it for His glory and for our good.

00:49:17.636 --> 00:49:18.997
Turn with me if you will to Revelation 4.

00:49:20.739 --> 00:49:22.181
We'll end here this morning Revelation 4.

00:49:37.319 --> 00:49:42.866
John is having his vision of heaven and as he's

00:49:44.354 --> 00:49:46.096
Sorry, that's a type of Revelation chapter five.

00:49:47.137 --> 00:49:54.505
As he's having this vision, he sees the scroll and there's great sorrow because no one is found who's worthy to open the scroll.

00:49:54.525 --> 00:49:59.130
And then he hears of this lion of the tribe of Judah who's going to come and open the scroll.

00:50:00.131 --> 00:50:05.076
This would have been what the Jewish audience would have expected, this great messianic power, right?

00:50:05.156 --> 00:50:11.023
This great military ruler who would have come in the name of the Lord to save his people.

00:50:11.043 --> 00:50:12.284
And certainly Jesus does that.

00:50:12.344 --> 00:50:14.226
Certainly Jesus is the lion

00:50:14.306 --> 00:50:15.348
of the tribe of Judah.

00:50:16.049 --> 00:50:19.033
But then he turns and sees what is maybe more accurate of Jesus.

00:50:20.355 --> 00:50:23.600
Verse six, in between the throne he saw the four living creatures among the elders.

00:50:24.462 --> 00:50:33.335
I saw a lamb standing as though it had been slain with seven horns and with seven eyes and with seven spirits of God sent out into all the earth.

00:50:33.796 --> 00:50:37.682
And he went and took the scroll from the hand of him who was seated on the throne.

00:50:37.954 --> 00:50:49.449
And when he had taken the scroll, the four living creatures and the 24 elders fell down before the lamb, each holding a harp and golden bowls full of incense, which are the prayers of the saints, and they sang a new song.

00:50:50.871 --> 00:50:55.016
Worthy are you to take the scroll and to open its seals.

00:50:55.517 --> 00:50:59.602
For you were slain and by your blood you ransomed a people

00:50:59.778 --> 00:51:10.251
For God, from every tribe and language and people and nation, and you have made them together a kingdom and priests to our God and they shall reign on the earth.

00:51:11.773 --> 00:51:16.239
Dear friend, Jesus is the lamb that met the criteria that God had set.

00:51:16.619 --> 00:51:19.623
He fulfilled the Old Testament prophecies of the coming Messiah.

00:51:19.944 --> 00:51:20.925
He came to this earth.

00:51:20.965 --> 00:51:22.146
He lived a sinless life.

00:51:22.447 --> 00:51:23.688
He died on a cross.

00:51:23.969 --> 00:51:25.010
He rose again.

00:51:25.890 --> 00:51:32.518
and is now seated at the right hand of God, the only one worthy of ruling with God for all of eternity.

00:51:32.958 --> 00:51:33.299
Why?

00:51:34.300 --> 00:51:37.524
To redeem a people for himself.

00:51:40.267 --> 00:51:46.614
The only logical answer to the question that I asked earlier, how could it be that God would send his son to be the Lamb of God is this.

00:51:46.654 --> 00:51:48.597
He did it for his glory.

00:51:48.717 --> 00:51:53.042
He did it because it would bring him praise and he did it for the benefit of his people.

00:51:56.322 --> 00:52:00.708
but that doesn't even seem to really satisfy the, the bigness of that question.

00:52:02.891 --> 00:52:06.115
So what should our response be to such a great mystery?

00:52:07.377 --> 00:52:15.808
My, I suggest that it's the same response of the 24 elders, same response for that matter of Israel, when they heard what was going to happen to worship.

00:52:17.670 --> 00:52:23.538
The point of Passover is that God's people whom he has redeemed might praise his matchless name.

00:52:24.962 --> 00:52:26.484
Really quick, I wanna read Psalms 113.

00:52:26.524 --> 00:52:33.954
This is from the Halal, which is the section of Psalms that was to be sung on the feast days.

00:52:33.994 --> 00:52:37.459
And this particular Psalm was too intended to be sung before the Passover meal.

00:52:38.420 --> 00:52:41.765
And this is what God gives to his people as a song to be sung before the meal.

00:52:42.706 --> 00:52:43.347
Praise the Lord.

00:52:43.847 --> 00:52:45.309
Praise O servants of the Lord.

00:52:45.970 --> 00:52:48.113
Praise the name of the Lord.

00:52:48.714 --> 00:52:51.698
Blessed be the name of the Lord from this time forth and forevermore.

00:52:52.418 --> 00:52:57.142
From the rising of the sun to its setting, from the name of the Lord is to be praised.

00:52:57.703 --> 00:53:00.766
The Lord is high above all nations, His glory above all the heavens.

00:53:01.246 --> 00:53:03.488
Who is like the Lord our God, who is seated on high?

00:53:03.889 --> 00:53:05.450
Who looks far down on the earth?

00:53:05.490 --> 00:53:09.274
Who looks far down on heavens and on the earth?

00:53:09.895 --> 00:53:16.341
He raises the poor from the dust and lifts the needy from the ash heap to make them sit with princes, with the princes of His people.

00:53:16.741 --> 00:53:22.066
He gives the barren woman a home, making her the joyous mother of children.

00:53:22.242 --> 00:53:23.644
praise the Lord.

00:53:25.487 --> 00:53:26.629
So what's the point of Passover?

00:53:27.470 --> 00:53:30.855
The point of Passover is that God's people would praise him.

00:53:32.157 --> 00:53:34.561
That God would redeem a people to praise him.

00:53:35.522 --> 00:53:39.328
And God does just that and God alone does just that in this text.

00:53:39.348 --> 00:53:51.186
So this morning if you're here and you're a believer, your response this morning is simply this, to praise, to wonder and exalt the Lord the fact that he has redeemed you.

00:53:53.186 --> 00:53:53.947
Praise the Lord.

00:53:54.849 --> 00:53:56.131
What other response do we have?

00:53:57.674 --> 00:54:03.123
If you're here this morning and you're not a believer, AKA, you've never turned from your sin and put your trust in the Lord alone.

00:54:04.165 --> 00:54:05.888
Let me ask you this one question as I close.

00:54:06.229 --> 00:54:08.352
What if just one Jew?

00:54:09.134 --> 00:54:12.139
What if just one of them had not heeded the warning?

00:54:13.982 --> 00:54:15.384
What if just one family said, you know what?

00:54:15.485 --> 00:54:16.807
I don't have time for that today.

00:54:17.568 --> 00:54:18.610
I'll do that tomorrow.

00:54:19.714 --> 00:54:20.996
I don't want to do that.

00:54:21.016 --> 00:54:23.299
I've got too much else going on that I want to do today.

00:54:23.359 --> 00:54:29.007
I'm not going to submit to what God wants me to do today because I want to do what I want to do today.

00:54:30.609 --> 00:54:32.071
What would have happened to that family?

00:54:33.773 --> 00:54:35.816
The same thing that happened to every Egyptian family.

00:54:37.178 --> 00:54:38.280
The firstborn would have died.

00:54:38.440 --> 00:54:43.006
God's justice would have been done on that family.

00:54:43.026 --> 00:54:46.030
Dear friend, if you're here this morning and you're not a believer, the message of the Bible is clear.

00:54:46.471 --> 00:54:48.754
Today is the day of salvation.

00:54:49.666 --> 00:54:51.189
Trust in the Lord.

00:54:51.249 --> 00:54:56.098
His promises are good and his plans are for his glory and for our good.

00:54:56.559 --> 00:55:06.158
And so this morning, if you're here and you have never trusted in him, may you see in this passage, God's goodness and his desire to redeem a people for himself.

00:55:06.979 --> 00:55:11.768
And this morning, if you're here and you don't know what that's like, I challenge you to come talk to an elder after service.

00:55:11.788 --> 00:55:12.690
Let me pray, Father.

00:55:12.834 --> 00:55:14.116
Thank you for your word this morning.

00:55:14.136 --> 00:55:19.503
God, thank you that you have, in your word, set forth a plan to redeem a people for yourself.

00:55:19.523 --> 00:55:26.252
God, thank you that in this Passover text, God, we find just a shadow of what is to come on the cross.

00:55:26.953 --> 00:55:35.164
God, thank you that what we see in Exodus, God, is a picture of the redemption that is to come for your people under the blood of your son.

00:55:36.566 --> 00:55:42.834
God, thank you for, God, just the work you did in redeeming Israel so that you could bring your son to us on this earth.

00:55:43.490 --> 00:55:46.733
God, thank you that you didn't do what was just that night.

00:55:47.754 --> 00:55:51.938
God, thank you that you allowed the blood to satisfy you for a night.

00:55:53.660 --> 00:56:09.414
But God also thank you that you didn't just make us continue to offer up perpetual sacrifices, but that you sent your son once for all, that there might be no more sacrifices, that he might be the perfect sacrifice so that everyone who calls upon his name shall be saved.

00:56:10.856 --> 00:56:13.298
God, may we carry that message to our family and friends.

00:56:13.666 --> 00:56:14.308
for your glory.

00:56:14.690 --> 00:56:17.218
And may we be a part of building your kingdom here on the earth.

00:56:17.239 --> 00:56:24.986
We pray this in your name.

00:56:25.006 --> 00:56:25.106
Amen.

00:56:45.698 --> 00:56:48.622
Thank you for listening to this sermon from Harvest Baptist Church.

00:56:49.223 --> 00:56:54.071
For more information about the church, please visit our website harvestbc.church.

00:56:54.932 --> 00:57:05.809
If you would like to contact us, please email us at contact.harvestbc.gmail.com or you can call us at 706-780-2211.

00:57:05.829 --> 00:57:14.482
If you are looking for a church home or visiting the North Georgia area, we would love for you to join us on a Sunday morning.

00:57:14.658 --> 00:57:21.297
at 9.30 in the fellowship hall for breakfast and Sunday school, and then at 11 a.m. for our Lord's Day worship service.

00:57:21.839 --> 00:57:23.062
We hope that you have a great week.

00:57:23.484 --> 00:57:24.306
God bless.
